# Amazon Linux EC2 Complete Deployment Guide 🚀

Ah, I see! You provisioned **Amazon Linux 2/2023** (which uses `ec2-user` and is RedHat/CentOS based) instead of Ubuntu. That is perfectly fine and often faster on AWS, but it uses `dnf` or `yum` instead of `apt`!

Because installing raw PostgreSQL natively on Amazon Linux can be much messier than Debian, the smartest and cleanest way to deploy your Next.js TurboRepo on Amazon Linux is via **Docker Compose**. You already have a perfect `docker-compose.yml` file sitting in your project waiting!

---

## 🛠️ Step 1: Install System Dependencies (Git, Docker)

On your EC2 terminal (`ec2-user@ip-...`), run these commands to install foundational software:

```bash
# Update the system
sudo dnf update -y

# Install Git and Docker
sudo dnf install -y git docker

# Start the Docker Service
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker

# Give your user permission to run Docker without typing "sudo" every time
sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user

# IMPORTANT: You must log out and log back in to apply the group permission!
# Type "exit" and SSH back in!
```

Wait, SSH back in before proceeding!

---

## 🐳 Step 2: Install Docker Compose

Docker Compose lets us spin up Next.js, Postgres, and Redis simultaneously from your one file!

```bash
# Download Docker-Compose plugin specifically for Amazon Linux
sudo curl -L "https://github.com/docker/compose/releases/latest/download/docker-compose-$(uname -s)-$(uname -m)" -o /usr/local/bin/docker-compose

# Apply execution permissions to the binary
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/docker-compose
```

---

## 📥 Step 3: Clone your Project & Configure Environment

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/your-username/your-cushion-repo.git
cd your-cushion-repo

# Create your production Environment Variables file
nano .env
```

Paste your `.env` secrets. Crucially, your `DATABASE_URL` *must* point to Docker's internal networking now (which I configured in your file earlier):

```env
# CRITICAL: It MUST say "@db" to route traffic inside the Docker network!
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:postgres@db:5432/cushion_saas?schema=public"

# Add standard AWS S3 and NextAuth keys
NEXTAUTH_SECRET="<generate-a-secure-string>"
NEXTAUTH_URL="http://<YOUR-EC2-PUBLIC-IP>"
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="..."
# ... and so on
```

*Save with `CTRL+X`, then `Y`, then `Enter`.*

---

## 🏗️ Step 4: Build and Launch Everything

Because of Docker Compose, building your Next.js app, fetching Prisma, setting up Redis, and spinning up PostgreSQL happens automatically.

```bash
# Spin up the containers in detached (background) mode
docker-compose up --build -d
```

This will take a few minutes as it downloads the Postgres/Redis images and compiles your Next.js app. 

---

## 🗄️ Step 5: Migrate your Database Tables

Once the containers are successfully running, we need to instruct Prisma (running securely *inside* the web container) to construct the database schema inside the Postgres container.

```bash
# Run prisma db push directly within the Next.js container!
# By default, docker-compose names your service "app" based on your docker-compose.yml
docker-compose exec app cd /app/packages/database && pnpm exec prisma db push
```

---

## 🎉 Step 6: Make sure AWS Security Groups are Open

Your application is now natively running on port `3000` on your instance!

1. Go to your **EC2 Dashboard** on AWS.
2. Select your instance -> Click **Security** -> Click your **Security Group ID**.
3. Edit **Inbound Rules** to ensure you allow:
   - **Type: Custom TCP**, Port: **3000**, Source: **0.0.0.0/0** (Anywhere IPv4)

**Congratulations, if you visit your EC2 IP Address in your browser (`http://<YOUR-IP>:3000`), the Cushion application is LIVE!**

*(Note: Depending on how your `next.config.js` or NextAuth works, you might eventually want to stick Nginx up front on port 80 to proxy port 3000 like in the previous guide, but Docker guarantees 100% stable execution environments for mono-repos!)*
